I have followed Hurricane Laura closely through out the day in hopes that we could be in school tomorrow but the storm has continued to intensify and will possibly hit land as a Category 5. For this reason we are canceling school for tomorrow, Thursday August 27th. I never want to make this decision in haste but I also realize you all need time to make alternate arrangements. Please be safe and keep the families in the path of this storm in your thoughts and prayers.

Thank you,
Gb

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.

P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

https://tea.texas.gov/sites/default/files/covid/covid19-how-to-apply-for-pebt-one-pager.pdf

The exact language of the order as it pertains to schools reads: “In accordance with the Guidelines from the President and the CDC, schools shall remain temporarily closed to in-person classroom attendance and shall not recommence before May 4, 2020.” Rusk Independent School District extended the closure of its campuses in compliance with the governor’s executive order.

While today’s announcement means the educational setting will continue to look different for several more weeks, we want our students, families and staff to know learning will continue. Having all students learn from home is a newer concept for RISD, however, we are committed to providing environments where our students thrive, read and excel.

The health and safety of our students and staff will remain core to our decisions in this rapidly changing and unique situation.

post_text:
#DifferenceMaker Award
At Rusk ISD we have challenged ourselves to #bethedifference in the lives that we touch. We strive to think of others first, to build passion and compassion, to be positive, optimistic and contagious, to stand out by serving, and to be intentional and purposeful in what we do to make the change that we want to see. We work to #bethedifference with our students, in our community, and with each other.
We are excited to present the Rusk ISD Difference Maker Award designed to recognize a person or group of people that are #DifferenceMakers.
Anyone may nominate a #DifferenceMaker. A committee of stakeholders will select a winner. Honors include recognition on district website, social media, local newspaper and recognition at a school board meeting, etc.
Please help us by nominating a Rusk ISD #DifferenceMaker today and #bethedifference for a better tomorrow.
NOMINATIONS ARE DUE BY JANUARY 17th.

Use the following link to nominate a #DifferenceMaker.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/differencemakernominations

GW Bradford Primary School would like to introduce their new Principal, Mrs. Crystal Nichols! Mrs. Nichols has been the Assistant Principal of GW Bradford since 2016. She is excited about her new role & will continue to strive for student excellence!

post_text:
January 17, 2019

Rusk ISD Community,

On Wednesday January 16th during the morning bus route a student was allegedly heard making a threatening statement. The campus Administration was notified immediately by transportation and the student was escorted to the office shortly after arrival. As soon as the student was thoroughly searched and questioned the campus took appropriate disciplinary action. Law enforcement was contacted and an investigation is currently being conducted. I want to thank our Transportation Department,Campus Administration, and the Rusk Police Department for their quick response and continued dedication to provide a safe environment for our students.

I want to remind and assure everyone that any threat made against Rusk ISD and it’s students will not be tolerated. Individuals who make threats will be dealt with immediately and the disciplinary action taken will be to the maximum extent allowed by law.

Grey Burton, Superintendent

post_text:
Pinwheels for Prevention
In 2008, Prevent Child Abuse America introduced the pinwheel as the new national symbol for child abuse prevention through Pinwheels for Prevention. By its very nature, the pinwheel connotes whimsy and childlike notions. In essence, it has come to serve as the physical embodiment, or reminder, of the great childhoods we want for all children.

All Rusk ISD Campuses will display Blue Pinwheels in front of their buildings for the month of April as we help to increase Child Abuse Awareness. Shining in the sun, the pinwheels represent a bright future for our children and our community.

In 2008, Prevent Child Abuse America introduced the pinwheel as the new national symbol for child abuse prevention through Pinwheels for Prevention. All Rusk ISD Campuses will display Blue Pinwheels in front of their buildings for the month of April as we help to increase Child Abuse Awareness. Shining in the sun, the pinwheels represent a bright future for our children and our community.

post_text: ❤️THANK YOU to all of these incredibly thoughtful businesses, organizations, and citizens for teaming up with the AMAZING 🌳Tree of Promise 🌳. They either donated school supplies and/or gave monetary donations for our Rusk ISD students to begin the school year well prepared. We appreciate YOU! If you see these people out and about or visit their business, please thank them personally for helping with this worthy cause. We are #EagleNation ! 🦅

From Coach Hancock:
George Cumby with Cumby Combine Camp Ministries will have a football skills camp at Jacksonville College this Saturday from 8:45 am to 2 pm. Registration is $10 each and it starts at 8. Camp is open to ages 6-14. Bring a water container...water is provided.
